'''Ahlbeck Pier''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Seebrücke Ahlbeck''  [[Polish language|Polish]]: ''Molo w Czerninie'') - a [[pier]] located in [[Ahlbeck]], on the island of [[Usedom]]; it is the oldest [[pier]] in [[Germany]]. The [[pier]] stretches from the ''Imperial Beach'' for 280 metres into the [[Baltic Sea]]. The [[pier]] has a restaurant and a [[jetty]] at the end of the pier primarily used for sightseeing tours in the [[Bay of Pomerania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahlbeck Pier|url=http://podrozepolskiemorzekompendiumwiedzy.blogspot.co.uk/2013/04/swinoujscie-w-najblizszym-sasiedztwie.html|website=Podróże Polskie Pomorze Kompendium Wiedzy|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>  

==History==

In 1882, a platform which extended from the promenade was built and housed a restaurant, in 1898 works began for the platform to be extended for 280 metres into the [[Baltic Sea]]. The main function of the [[pier]] was to function as a [[jetty]] for [[Sailing ship|sailing ships]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahlbeck History|url=http://www.usedom01.republika.pl/ahlbeck.html|website=Uznam|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> 

In 1905, the [[pier]] was joined with the platform which housed the restaurant. In 1926, the [[canvas]] [[boardwalk]] located in the mid-section of the [[pier]] was replaced with [[Wood|wooden]] [[Plank (wood)|planks]]. Throughout the [[pier]]'s existence it has undergone many renovations to replace any rotten elements. In 1970 to 1973 the pier had undergone a major reconstruction in which the [[Wood|wooden]] [[Column|pillars]] and structure was replaced with [[steel]] [[Girder|girders]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahlbeck Pier|url=http://www.seebruecke-ahlbeck.de/speisekarte.html|website=Seebruecke Ahlbeck|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> 

