The '''European Unit of Account''' (EUA) was a [[unit of account]] used in the [[European Communities]] from 1975 to 1979, when it was replaced at parity by the [[European Currency Unit]], in turn replaced at parity in 1999 by the [[euro]].
Initially it was used for [[Lomé Convention]] and [[European Investment Bank]] operations before being gradually introduced into other sectors of Community activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europeaninstitute.org/EU-Facts/timeline-of-the-european-union.html |title=Timeline of the European Union &#124; EU Facts |publisher=Europeaninstitute.org |date= |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref>
The EUA was a basket of European currencies, originally designed to have the same value in mid-1974 as the IMF [[special drawing rights]] basket, both worth US$1.20635; they immediately moved apart in value. Different units of account had previously been used for different purposes, including the budget, the [[European Coal and Steel Community]], and the [[Common Agriculture Policy]]<ref>[http://aei.pitt.edu/7861/01/31735055281731_1.pdf The Units of Account as a Factor of Integration] CEC 87/75</ref> following the abandonment of the [[gold parity unit of account]] in the early 1970s in the wake of the collapse of the [[Bretton Woods system]].<ref name=eupf>[http://www.biblioteca.porto.ucp.pt/docbweb/multimedia/associa/pdf/eur_u.pdf European Union Public Finance]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, European Commission, {{ISBN|92-894-1620-3}}, published 2002, accessed 20112-01-09</ref>
==Bond market baskets of currencies== Various European [[currency basket]]s were used as units of account in international [[bond market]]s. Some of these were defined in [[ISO 4217]].<ref>[http://www.iso.org/iso/support/faqs/faqs_widely_used_standards/widely_used_standards_other/currency_codes/currency_codes_list-1.htm ISO currency codes list]</ref>
